    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Selliguea soridens are derived from its leaves and involve various methods to extract its bioactive compounds. Tea is made by steeping the leaves in hot water, releasing flavonoids and saponins that may help reduce inflammation and improve cardiovascular health. Infusion is similar to tea but typically involves cold water and a higher leaf-to-water ratio, which can enhance the extraction of volatile compounds such as alkaloids and terpenes. A tincture is a concentrated liquid extract of the plant's leaves, which can be used to treat conditions like fever and respiratory issues due to its antimicrobial properties. Decoction and salve preparations involve boiling the leaves in water to create a concentrated liquid and mixing it with oils or fats respectively, to treat skin conditions and wounds.",
