    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Selliguea soridens improperly are that individuals may experience nausea due to its hepatotoxic properties, which can lead to liver damage if not used correctly. Furthermore, Selliguea soridens can cause dizziness and headaches due to its neurotoxic effects, which can be exacerbated by improper use. Additionally, users may experience diarrhea as a result of the plant's emetic properties, which can lead to dehydration and electrolyte imbalances if not treated promptly. These side effects are often the result of the plant's high levels of aristolochic acid, a known nephrotoxin and carcinogen. Inadequate knowledge of the plant's properties and proper usage can lead to severe and long-lasting health consequences.",
    "uses": "Selliguea soridens, a species of fern, is often used in traditional medicine in various parts of the world. Its medicinal uses are attributed to its antifungal and antibacterial properties. The plant is believed to have anti-inflammatory properties, which may help in treating various health conditions. In some cultures, it is used to treat skin conditions, such as eczema and acne. Further research is needed to confirm the effectiveness of Selliguea soridens in treating these conditions.",
    "taxonomy": "Selliguea soridens, also known as the lesser umbrella fern, is a species of fern in the family Polypodiaceae. The family Polypodiaceae is a group of vascular plants that are classified under the division Pteridophyta. Pteridophyta is a division of plants that are non-flowering, vascular plants, and are commonly known as ferns and horsetails. The kingdom to which Pteridophyta belongs is Plantae, which encompasses all vascular plants. The classification of Selliguea soridens can be summarized as: kingdom Plantae, division Pteridophyta, class Polypodiopsida, family Polypodiaceae, genus Selliguea.",
    "benefits": "Selliguea soridens, a plant species native to the tropical regions of Asia, has been traditionally used in herbal medicine. It is reported to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may contribute to its potential health benefits. The plant is said to have been used to treat various conditions, including fever, rheumatism, and respiratory issues. Its leaves and roots are often used to make infusions and decoctions, which are believed to possess medicinal properties. Further research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of Selliguea soridens for medicinal use.",
    "parts": "Selliguea soridens, also known as the spotted spleenwort, is a species of fern found in tropical regions. The medicinal properties of Selliguea soridens are primarily attributed to its leaves, which are used in traditional medicine to treat various ailments. The leaves are said to possess anti-inflammatory, antibacterial, and antifungal properties. In some parts of the world, the leaves are used to treat fever, cough, and digestive issues. However, more research is needed to fully understand the potential health benefits and risks associated with using Selliguea soridens as a medicinal plant.",
    "intro": "Selliguea soridens, also known as Leptochilus soridens, is a species of flowering plant in the family Polypodiaceae, commonly referred to as a type of fern. The plant is valued for its traditional medicinal uses, which include reducing inflammation and improving cardiovascular health due to its ability to lower blood pressure and cholesterol levels. Bioactive constituents of Selliguea soridens include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional herbal medicine, Selliguea soridens is often prepared as a tea or tincture, and is also used in combination with other herbs to make capsules and tablets."
